		<title>Stitch Raises $25M Series A Led by Andreessen Horowitz</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/stitch-raises-25m-series-a-led-by-andreessen-horowitz/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 14 May 2026 10:53:25 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=201176</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Stitch, a financial operating system tailored for new-style organisations, has closed a $25 million Series A. It was led by Andreessen Horowitz, also known as a16z, which is the first</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/stitch-raises-25m-series-a-led-by-andreessen-horowitz/" data-wpel-link="internal">Stitch Raises $25M Series A Led by Andreessen Horowitz</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://stitch.co/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Stitch</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, a financial operating system tailored for new-style organisations, has closed a $25 million Series A. It was led by Andreessen Horowitz, also known as a16z, which is the first </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/nvision-raises-55m-to-expand-quantum-healthcare-tech/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">investment </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">by the Silicon Valley technology giant in the GCC.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Stitch also had a lot of existing investors in the round, including Arbor Ventures, COTU Ventures, Raed Ventures and the Saudi Venture Capital Company (SVC). The fresh round of investment raises Stitch&#8217;s total funding to date to $35M, following a year of exponential growth where the company&#8217;s revenues have increased twentyfold over the past 12 months.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the &#8220;Infrastructure Debt&#8221; Crisis</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Based in Riyadh, Stitch is trying to define itself as the platform on which all financial institutions run their software worldwide. The company claims that despite spending in excess of $1 trillion over the last few years on digital transformation, banks essentially have paid a lavish &#8220;veneer&#8221; over legacy systems.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This problem, said to be infrastructure debt by the outgoing FCA chairman, has emerged as a major barrier to innovation and the wider use of technology such as generative AI. With no single clean system of record, financial institutions find it difficult to provide good data to such a system or launch new products without risking total failure.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_201182" style="width: 490px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-201182" class="size-full wp-image-201182" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Stitch_main_-logo.jpg" alt="Stitch logo" width="480" height="87" /><p id="caption-attachment-201182" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Stitch</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">A cloud-native alternative to Stitch&#8217;s platform is available. It is a modular suite of tools for lending, card issuance, payments, and ledgers. Instead of a &#8220;rip and replace&#8221;, banks and fintechs can build the most modern part of the stack by adding individual modules one at a time.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/nvision-raises-55m-to-expand-quantum-healthcare-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">NVision Raises $55M to Expand Quantum Healthcare Tech</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Regional Growth and Global Ambition</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The timing of this investment could not be better given the major shift occurring in the Middle Eastern financial market. With efforts such as Saudi Arabia’s Vision 2030, the region is increasingly positioning itself at the epicentre of global fintech. Stitch has already established itself with big clients like Raya Financing, LuLu Exchange, and Foodics.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">In the last 6 months alone, the fintech has processed over $5 billion worth of transactions. While the company currently operates in the Gulf Cooperation Countries (GCC), Africa (Egypt and Kenya), and Southeast Asia, Stitch plans to deploy the Series A funds towards an expansive global strategy and strengthen its product engineering.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By offering a consolidated platform that expedites product implementations by up to 80%, Stitch empowers traditional financial institutions to replicate the agility of contemporary startups. The firm’s vision is to allow institutions to deploy new financial services in as little as three months, compared to the conventional year-long timeframe.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/stitch-raises-25m-series-a-led-by-andreessen-horowitz/" data-wpel-link="internal">Stitch Raises $25M Series A Led by Andreessen Horowitz</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
